\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Categorical-Physical Commutation Relations. (a) Frobenius norms of all nine commutators $[\hat  {O}_{\mathrm  {cat}},\hat  {O}_{\mathrm  {phys}}]$ displayed as a lollipop plot; all norms are $\leq 6.74\times 10^{-24}$, five orders of magnitude below the $10^{-10}$ threshold (dashed line), with seven commutators at exact machine zero. (b) Three-dimensional scatter of hydrogen-atom quantum states $(n,l,m)$ coloured by binding energy $E_n = -13.6/n^2$~eV, illustrating the categorical partition of the Hilbert space. (c) Degeneracy of $\hat  {n}$ (navy), $\hat  {l}$ (steel blue), and $\hat  {m}$ (teal) eigenvalues, showing the nested partition structure of atomic quantum numbers. (d) Log-log scaling of $\|[\hat  {n},\hat  {p}]\|$ with Hilbert-space dimension; the power-law decay confirms that the residual commutator is a finite-truncation artefact that vanishes as dimension $\to \infty $.}}{9}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:panel3_commutation}{{2}{9}{Categorical-Physical Commutation Relations. (a) Frobenius norms of all nine commutators $[\hat {O}_{\mathrm {cat}},\hat {O}_{\mathrm {phys}}]$ displayed as a lollipop plot; all norms are $\leq 6.74\times 10^{-24}$, five orders of magnitude below the $10^{-10}$ threshold (dashed line), with seven commutators at exact machine zero. (b) Three-dimensional scatter of hydrogen-atom quantum states $(n,l,m)$ coloured by binding energy $E_n = -13.6/n^2$~eV, illustrating the categorical partition of the Hilbert space. (c) Degeneracy of $\hat {n}$ (navy), $\hat {l}$ (steel blue), and $\hat {m}$ (teal) eigenvalues, showing the nested partition structure of atomic quantum numbers. (d) Log-log scaling of $\|[\hat {n},\hat {p}]\|$ with Hilbert-space dimension; the power-law decay confirms that the residual commutator is a finite-truncation artefact that vanishes as dimension $\to \infty $}{figure.2}{}}
\newlabel{thm:comparison}{{5.3}{9}{Comparison with Forward Search}{theorem.5.3}{}}
